f=Engineering/raj/custom/data-access-discipline/SKILL.md · in=data-access-discipline raj's backend talks dana's datastores: efficiently (no N+1, right-sized queries, connection pooling), correctly (transactions proper boundaries), within charter (reads grant; write/destructive change dana's migration script operator runs Rail backend side). It's seam between service layer data layer, seams bugs live. · p=backend data-access sins committed: ORM fires N+1 queries, missing transaction leaves half-written state, connection leak exhausts pool, charter-critical one application code runs destructive data change directly instead routing through dana operator. skill keeps seam clean. · wu=Triggers: "query database API," "why endpoint slow" (DB-bound), "transaction," "N+1," "connection pool," any backend code reads (attempts to) write data. · st:/ Protocol=`Backend code accessing data \· -> READS: right-sized (select what's used), no N+1 (batch/join/eager-load), paginated at the edge \· -> TRANSACTIONS: correct boundaries (all-or-nothing where needed), no long-held locks \· -> POOLING: connections pooled, released, never leaked; timeouts (service-patterns) \· -> WRITES / destructive changes: NOT executed by the backend directly.` · in=**No N+1, ever knowingly.** Fetching list querying item default ORM trap top backend performance killer (dana/db-performance's concern, raj's origin). Batch, join, eager-load; N+1 diff review finding (it's kind thing agent-generated data access introduces silently dev's integrity check). **Right-size reads.** Select columns/fields actually used, `SELECT discard; paginate API edge (api-standards). Over-fetching bandwidth, memory, latency nothing. **Transactions real boundaries.** Operations atomic one transaction (all-or-nothing); transactions short (no long-held locks block others service-patterns' cascade risk). multi-step mutation without transaction half-written-state bug. **Pool release connections.** Connections come pool, released promptly, never leak; leaked connection pool slow-motion outage. Pair service-patterns' timeouts. **Charter line: backend doesn't destructive data changes.** Reads within granted scope, fine. schema changes scaled create/update/delete/drop/truncate run application code they're dana's migration scripts operator executes (Rail 3). handler drops mass-mutates data top-severity charter breach, caught review. backend-side enforcement dana's authoring rule. **The access reflects dana's model.** Queries respect schema's constraints relationships; fighting model query layer means model query wrong (route dana). · of=`## Data Access: [endpoint/operation] \· Reads: [right-sized ✓ \· no N+1 ✓ \· paginated ✓] \· Transactions: [boundaries correct ✓] \· Pooling: [pooled + released ✓] \· Charter: [reads in scope ✓ \· NO backend-executed destructive change ✓ — schema/bulk = dana+operator (Rail 3)] \· Model fit: [respects dana schema ✓ / mismatch → dana]` · pr=**No knowing N+1** batch/join/eager-load; N+1 diff finding., **Right-size reads** select what's used; over-fetch waste., **Transactions real, short boundaries** atomic needed, long locks., **Pool release; never leak** leaked pool slow outage., **The backend never runs destructive data changes** schema/bulk dana authors, operator runs (Rail 3)., **Access reflects model** fighting schema means model query wrong. · f=ORM makes N+1 easy path configure eager-loading explicitly; ORM hides query behavior, log/inspect actual queries (dana's query-plan discipline) rather trust it., genuine bulk backend write seems needed it's dana migration (Rail 3), backend code; reshape it. "The app needs update million rows" migration, request handler., Transaction spans services don't (distributed transactions smell); use idempotency sagas/compensation (service-patterns) instead. · b:with Other Skills=**dana**: owns stores authors migrations; backend's disciplined, read-mostly access them, enforcement point Rail backend side., **dana/db-performance**: N+1 slow queries joint origin often here, diagnosis there., **service-patterns** (sibling): timeouts pooling calls., **api-standards** (sibling): pagination edge bounds what fetches., **quinn/charter-enforcement**: backend-executed destructive Rail breach caught gate., **aegis**: injection surfaces query construction route secure-code-review.